    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Melissa, whenever the weather decides to cooperate, I predict that you and rhubarb are going to be fast friends &#8211; if not lovers.  Watch out, Manuel!</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-3701" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Janet</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2006/03/winter-spring-pie/#comment-3701"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2006-06-05T04:20:00-04:00">Monday, June 5, 2006 at 4:20 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>First rhubarb of my garden this year. Made a strawberry rhubarb pie and it was wonderful except that it was way too juicy as it just couldn&#8217;t thicken. Did it again today with more flour and it was the same. Any suggestions?  Love you blog!</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-3702" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/01493708300940204826" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Molly</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2006/03/winter-spring-pie/#comment-3702"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2006-06-06T19:48:00-04:00">Tuesday, June 6, 2006 at 7:48 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Thank you, Janet!  But hmmm, I&#8217;m not sure what to tell you.  If more flour didn&#8217;t do the trick, well, hmmm.  I&#8217;m not sure it would make any difference, but you could try using tapioca as a thickener instead &#8211; some people prefer it over flour.  You might give it a try.</></>Either way, a runny pie is better than no pie at all, right?</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
